==See also==
* {{ill|Nathan Hale|en|Nathan Hale|qid=Q465574|lt=Nathan Hale|1=Nathan Hale}}— {{ill|Americans|en|Americans|qid=Q846570|lt=American|1=Americans}} {{ill|Patriot (American Revolution)|en|Patriot (American Revolution)|qid=Q1365374|lt=Patriot|1=Patriot (American Revolution)}}, soldier, and spy for the {{ill|Continental Army|en|Continental Army|qid=Q54122|lt=Continental Army|1=Continental Army}} during the {{ill|American Revolutionary War|en|American Revolutionary War|qid=Q40949|lt=American Revolutionary War|1=American Revolutionary War}}. He volunteered for an intelligence-gathering mission in {{ill|New York City|en|New York City|qid=Q60|lt=New York City|1=New York City}} but was captured by the {{ill|British people|en|British people|qid=Q842438|lt=British|1=British people}} and executed by {{ill|hanging|en|hanging|qid=Q175111|lt=hanging|1=Hanging}}. His last words were, reportedly, "I only regret that I have but one life to lose for my country." If he was intending to paraphrase or quote anyone, however, it was likely {{ill|Joseph Addison|en|Joseph Addison|qid=Q206384|lt=Joseph Addison|1=Joseph Addison}}'s play {{ill|Cato, a Tragedy|en|Cato, a Tragedy|qid=Q5053587|lt=Cato, a Tragedy|1=Cato, a Tragedy}} and not Kusunoki Masashige.
* {{ill|Otoya Yamaguchi|en|Otoya Yamaguchi|qid=Q469406|lt=Otoya Yamaguchi|1=Otoya Yamaguchi}}— 17-year-old Japanese right-wing {{ill|Ultranationalism|en|Ultranationalism|qid=Q38352698|lt=ultranationalist|1=Ultranationalism}} who assassinated socialist politician [[:en:Inejiro Asanuma|Inejiro Asanuma]] during a televised debate in 1960. After being arrested and interrogated, Yamaguchi committed suicide in a detention facility less than three weeks after the assassination. Before committing suicide, Yamaguchi wrote with toothpaste on his cell wall, "Long live the {{ill|Emperor|en|Emperor|qid=Q39018|lt=Emperor|1=Emperor}}" (天皇陛下万才, ''tennōheika banzai'') and "Would that I had seven lives to give for my country" (七生報国, ''shichishō hōkoku'')).

